eady, submit the vote.\n\nBut first, I need to execute the initial wait_for_opportunity call.\n\nLet me structure that. The mcp command needs to be called with tool and args.\n\nSo the tool call would be:\n\n{\n  \"name\": \"mcp\",\n  \"arguments\": {\n    \"tool\": \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\",\n    \"args\": \"{}\"\n  }\n}\n\nWait, the instructions say that the args must be a JSON string, so yes, the arguments for mcp's args parameter should be the string \"{}\".\n\nThen I need to wait for the response. But since I have to execute this in the current session, I'll make that first call.\n\nAssuming the response comes back. Let's say the first call returns state: waiting. Then I need to get the after_version from that response and call again with that value.\n\nBut since the system will handle the response in the next step, but as an AI, I have to make the calls one by one.\n\nBut the user's instruction says to start with calling aar_wait_for_opportunity with empty args. So my first step is to make that call.\n\nSo the first action is to invoke mcp with those parameters.\n\nLet me check the instructions again: \"Every mcp call must have exactly this shape: a tool string and an args string. Do not include action, server, or connect. Do not pass args as an object.\"\n\nSo in the mcp call, args is a JSON string. So for the first call, args is \"{}\", which is a string.\n\nSo in the tool call JSON, arguments should have \"tool\": \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\", \"args\": \"{}\".\n\nYes.\n\nSo the first step is to execute that mcp call.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_0f05542e20cf40809e7c85","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_wait_for_opportunity","args":"{}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":2406,"output":578,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":2984,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp"