re's PX-3, an Indian Express report, which says Iran closed the western half of airspace, citing the NOTAM, and lists the eight airports remaining operational.\n\nDefendant's evidence includes DX-D, FAA Q-code decode: QFALC indicates aerodrome closed, not airspace closure. DX-E shows airport code mapping: the NOTAM's exception list includes OISS/SYZ (Shiraz) but none of the other four listed airports (IKA, THR, MHD, IFN) are in the exception list. So for the two-listed-airports path, only Shiraz is an exception, which doesn't meet two airports.\n\nBut the rule's first path is \"broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region.\" The NOTAM is about airports in the west Tehran FIR. The FIR covers a large airspace region. However, the Q-code QFALC is aerodrome-related. The FAA doc says the Q-code decode doesn't specify airspace overflight; the plain text must be read.\n\nThe NOTAM text says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed ones. But airports being closed could affect arrivals/departures at those airports, but what about transit? The rule requires \"transiting, arriving in, and departing from\" the airspace or region. If only airports are closed but overflights are allowed, does that count?\n\nThe NOTAM says \"all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed except...\", but doesn't mention airways or overflights. The Q-code is for aerodrome, not airway. So perhaps the closure is limited to airports, not the entire airspace. For transit (overflying), the NOTAM doesn't say anything. So commercial flights transiting through the FIR would not be affected, only those landing or taking off at the airports. \n\nBut the rule says \"transiting, arriving in, and departing from\". If the airports are closed, then arriving and departing is suspended. But transiting requires the airspace to be blocked. However, typically, if all airports in a region are closed, transiting flights might reroute, but the NOTAM may not explicitly prohibit overflights.\n\nThe defendant argues that the QFALC is aerodrome closure, not airspace closure. The FAA note says the code doesn't include airspace overflight details. The NOTAM text says \"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\" – but FIR (Flight Information Region) is a designated airspace. Closing all airports in the FIR doesn't necessarily mean the airspace is closed. Airports are on the ground; the airspace above might still be used for transiting. \n\nBut how does that work? If airports are closed, meaning flights can't land or take off, but overflights might be okay. However, if there's a closure of airspace, that affects all aircraft in that airspace. But the NOTAM is about airports being closed. \n\nThe rule's definition says \"a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region\". If all airports in the west Tehran FIR are closed, then arriving and departing from those airports is suspended. But what about transiting through the FIR? The NOTAM doesn't say anything about transiting. However, if all airports in the region are closed, but overflights are allowed, maybe the \"transiting\" aspect isn't covered. But if the airports are closed, the main impact is on arrivals and departures. However, the rule includes \"transiting, arriving in, and departing from\" – so perhaps suspending arrivals and departures at multiple airports in a region could count as part of the requirement, but transiting needs to be suspended as well. \n\nThe defendant's argument is that the QFALC code is for aerodrome closure, so it's airport-specific, not airspace. The FAA doc confirms that the Q-code for aerodrome doesn't dictate airspace routes. The NOTAM's text is about airports, so it might not cover transiting flights in the airspace. \n\nLooking at the mark