n Ayatollah Jami International Airport\",30.367887,48.230075,10,AS,Iran,IR,\"Khuzestan Province\",IR-06,06,Abadan,1,OIAA,OIAA,ABD,,,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abadan_Airport,\"Abadan Airport, فرودگاه بین‌المللی آبادان\",1000,2026-01-21T17:04:05+00:00\n5197,OISS,large_airport,\"Shiraz Shahid Dastghaib International Airport\",29.5392,52.589802,4927,AS,Iran,IR,\"Fars Province\",IR-07,07,Shiraz,1,OISS,OISS,SYZ,,http://shirazairport.ir/,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shiraz_International_Airport,,1200,2022-11-20T21:49:09+00:00\n5206,OIYY,medium_airport,\"Shahid Sadooghi Airport\",31.9048995972,54.2765007019,4054,AS,Iran,IR,\"Yazd Province\",IR-21,21,Yazd,1,OIYY,OIYY,AZD,,,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shahid_Sadooghi_Airport,,750,2010-08-30T18:51:30+00:00\n5149,OICC,medium_airport,\"Shahid Ashrafi Esfahani Airport\",34.3459014893,47.1581001282,4307,AS,Iran,IR,\"Kermanshah Province\",IR-05,05,Kermanshah,1,OICC,OICC,KSH,,,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shahid_Ashrafi_Esfahani_Airport,,750,2010-08-30T18:50:18+00:00\n5159,OIGG,medium_airport,\"Sardar-e-Jangal Airport\",37.323333,49.617778,-40,AS,Iran,IR,\"Gilan Province\",IR-01,01,Rasht,1,OIGG,OIGG,RAS,,http://rasht.airport.ir/HomePage.aspx?site=rasht.airport&lang=fa-IR&tabid=0,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rasht_Airport,,750,2012-12-12T10:16:02+00:00\n5137,OIAW,large_airport,\"Qasem Soleimani International Airport\",31.3364,48.763789,66,AS,Iran,IR,\"Khuzestan Province\",IR-06,06,Ahvaz,1,OIAW,OIAW,AWZ,,http://ahwaz.airport.ir/,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ahvaz_International_Airport,\"Ahvaz, Ahvaz International Airport, Ahwaz\",1000,2026-01-20T04:09:04+00:00\n\nObservation: of the five market-listed airports, the PX-2 exception list explicitly includes OISS/SYZ (Shiraz) but does not list OIIE/IKA, OIII/THR, OIMM/MHD, or OIFM/IFN.\n\n[defendant] DX-S1 Market rule text including transiting/arriving/departing requirement\n# Market page record\n\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\n\n## Event\n\n- event id: 438327\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: True\n- event closed: False\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\n\n## May 24 market\n\n- market id: 2241873\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\n- active: True\n- closed: False\n- acceptingOrders: True\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"0.157\", \"0.843\"]\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\n\n## Rule text\n\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\n\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\n\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\n\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\n\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\n\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-S2 Raw NOTAM text showing airport/aerodrome focus\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAM A1010/26, https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\nRetrieved: 2026-06-19T22:45:00Z\n\nPage title/summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\n\nPeriod of applicability shown by page (UTC): 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n\nInterpretation shown by page: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\n\nRaw NOTAM shown by page:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCustody note: This is a Notamify public NOTAM page capture, not a direct Iranian CAA server response. It preserves the raw NOTAM text and timing displayed by Notamify. Spelling of 'OPRATION' appears as shown in the raw NOTAM display.\n\n[defendant] DX-S3 QFALC decode as aerodrome closed\nSource: FAA, Order 7930.2 Appendix B, International NOTAM (Q) Codes, https://www.faa.gov/air_traffic/publications/atpubs/notam_html/appendix_b.html\nRetrieved: 2026-06-19T22:52:30Z\n\nRelevant captured text:\n\nThis appendix is to be used to interpret the contents of coded international NOTAMs. A NOTAM code group contains five letters.\n\nThe first letter is always the letter \"Q\" to indicate a code abbreviation for use in the composition of NOTAMs.\n\nThe second and third letters identify the subject being reported. The fourth and fifth letters identify the status of operation of the subject being reported.\n\nSecond and Third Letter Decode Tables, AGA Facilities and Services (F):\nFA - Aerodrome - ad\n\nFourth and Fifth Letter Decode Tables, Limitations (L):\nLC - Closed - clsd\n\nApplication to PX-2: the NOTAM code shown in PX-2 is QFALC. Under the FAA/ICAO-style decode table, FA identifies the subject as an aerodrome and LC identifies the status as closed. This decoding does not by itself state an airspace-route or FIR overflight closure; the operative plain text must still be read for scope.\n\n[defendant] DX-S4 Airport-code mapping and secondary-report conflict\nSource: OurAirports Iran airports CSV, https://ourairports.com/countries/IR/airports.csv\nRetrieved: 2026-06-19T22:52:45Z\nMethod: curl -sL https://ourairports.com/countries/IR/airports.csv | grep -E 'OIIE|OIII|OIMM|OISS|OIFM|OITR|OIKK|OIAA|OIYY|OICC|OIGG|OIAW'\n\nCaptured CSV lines for the five market-listed airports:\n5166,OIIE,large_airport,\"Imam Khomeini International Airport\",35.416099548339844,51.152198791503906,3305,AS,Iran,IR,\"Tehran Province\",IR-23,23,Tehran,1,OIIE,OIIE,IKA,,http://www.ikia.ir/,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imam_Khomeini_International_Airport,Ahmadabad,1200,2008-06-13T14:30:04+00:00\n5168,OIII,large_airport,\"Mehrabad International Airport\",35.689175,51.314392,3962,AS,Iran,IR,\"Tehran Province\",IR-23,23,Tehran,1,OIII,OIII,THR,,,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mehrabad_International_Airport,,1200,2026-02-12T14:59:19+00:00\n5183,OIMM,large_airport,\"Mashhad International Airport\",36.234821,59.642949,3263,AS,Iran,IR,\"Razavi Khorasan Province\",IR-09,09,Mashhad,1,OIMM,OIMM,MHD,,https://mashhad.airport.ir/,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mashhad_International_Airport,\"Shahid Hashemi Nejad Airport, Mashhad Shahid Hasheminejad International Airport\",1200,2026-01-20T04:11:27+00:00\n5197,OISS,large_airport,\"Shiraz Shahid Dastghaib International Airport\",29.5392,52.589802,4927,AS,Iran,IR,\"Fars Province\",IR-07,07,Shiraz,1,OISS,OISS,SYZ,,http://shirazairport.ir/,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shiraz_International_Airport,,1200,2022-11-20T21:49:09+00:00\n5156,OIFM,large_airport,\"Isfahan Shahid Beheshti International Airport\",32.755142,51.883877,5059,AS,Iran,IR,\"Isfahan Province\",IR-10,10,Isfahan,1,OIFM,OIFM,IFN,,,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isfahan_International_Airport,Esfahan,1000,2026-01-09T23:44:47+00:00\n\nCaptured CSV lines for the eight airport identifiers excepted in PX-2 raw NOTAM text:\n5203,OITR,medium_airport,\"Urmia Airport\",37.6680984497,45.0686988831,4343,AS,Iran,IR,\"West Azerbaijan Province\",IR-04,04,Urmia,1,OITR,OITR,OMH,,,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Urmia_Airport,,750,2010-08-30T13:04:12+00:00\n5174,OIKK,large_airport,\"Ayatollah Hashemi Rafsanjani International Airport\",30.271276,56.949692,5741,AS,Iran,IR,\"Kerman Province\",IR-08,08,Kerman,1,OIKK,OIKK,KER,,,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ayatollah_Hashemi_Rafsanjani_Airport,,1000,2026-01-09T23:40:26+00:00\n5130,OIAA,large_airport,\"Abadan Ayatollah Jami International Airport\",30.367887,48.230075,10,AS,Iran,IR,\"Khuzestan Province\",IR-06,06,Abadan,1,OIAA,OIAA,ABD,,,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abadan_Airport,\"Abadan Airport, فرودگاه بین‌المللی آبادان\",1000,2026-01-21T17:04:05+00:00\n5197,OISS,large_airport,\"Shiraz Shahid Dastghaib International Airport\",29.5392,52.589802,4927,AS,Iran,IR,\"Fars Province\",IR-07,07,Shiraz,1,OISS,OISS,SYZ,,http://shirazairport.ir/,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shiraz_International_Airport,,1200,2022-11-20T21:49:09+00:00\n5206,OIYY,medium_airport,\"Shahid Sadooghi Airport\",31.9048995972,54.2765007019,4054,AS,Iran,IR,\"Yazd Province\",IR-21,21,Yazd,1,OIYY,OIYY,AZD,,,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shahid_Sadooghi_Airport,,750,2010-08-30T18:51:30+00:00\n5149,OICC,medium_airport,\"Shahid Ashrafi Esfahani Airport\",34.3459014893,47.1581001282,4307,AS,Iran,IR,\"Kermanshah Province\",IR-05,05,Kermanshah,1,OICC,OICC,KSH,,,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shahid_Ashrafi_Esfahani_Airport,,750,2010-08-30T18:50:18+00:00\n5159,OIGG,medium_airport,\"Sardar-e-Jangal Airport\",37.323333,49.617778,-40,AS,Iran,IR,\"Gilan Province\",IR-01,01,Rasht,1,OIGG,OIGG,RAS,,http://rasht.airport.ir/HomePage.aspx?site=rasht.airport&lang=fa-IR&tabid=0,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rasht_Airport,,750,2012-12-12T10:16:02+00:00\n5137,OIAW,large_airport,\"Qasem Soleimani International Airport\",31.3364,48.763789,66,AS,Iran,IR,\"Khuzestan Province\",IR-06,06,Ahvaz,1,OIAW,OIAW,AWZ,,http://ahwaz.airport.ir/,https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ahvaz_International_Airport,\"Ahvaz, Ahvaz International Airport, Ahwaz\",1000,2026-01-20T04:09:04+00:00\n\nObservation: of the five market-listed airports, the PX-2 exception list explicitly includes OISS/SYZ (Shiraz) but does not list OIIE/IKA, OIII/THR, OIMM/MHD, or OIFM/IFN.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Notamify capture of Iran NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 (ev_a6870de8ffed_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-a6870de8ffed)\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\nSHA-256: `a6870de8ffed7d8cae93dd5e233bfbb041ccda9493c8db97496a0ffeead27054`\nBytes: 1458\nRelevance: Primary-like NOTAM archive capture showing Iran OIIX A1010/26 effective 2026-05-22 20:46 UTC to 2026-05-25 08:30 UTC, closing airports in the west part of Tehran FIR with limited listed-airport exceptions and CAA permission requirement for civil IFR passenger flights.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace closure, May 23 2026 (ev_16946d327688_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-16946d327688)\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\nSHA-256: `16946d327688bbaa873990e242a55c93c46d05f188bc7ad4651bb9c1abe3548b`\nBytes: 2063\nRelevance: Credible secondary reporting corroborating the NOTAM source, Iran Civil Aviation Authority issuance, May 22-May 25 window, eight-airport exception list including listed market airports, daylight-only restrictions, fresh CAA approval requirement, and commercial rerouting.\n\n[defendant arguments] FAA International NOTAM Q-code decode for QFALC (ev_a516424b54be_submitted-evidence-03-defendant-a516424b54be)\nSource: https://www.faa.gov/air_traffic/publications/atpubs/notam_html/appendix_b.html\nSHA-256: `a516424b54be20e47eea237ca0ec110ca73d452356bfe11fca0f98f6a207fd9f`\nBytes: 1095\nRelevance: Decodes plaintiff's PX-2 NOTAM code QFALC as an aerodrome-closure notice, relevant to whether the notice proves an airspace-region closure or only airport closures/permissions.\n\n[defendant arguments] OurAirports Iran airport code extract for market-listed and NOTAM-excepted airports (ev_d767617fb81e_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-d767617fb81e)\nSource: https://ourairports.com/countries/IR/airports.csv\nSHA-256: `d767617fb81ee90a4fac9440332aab2a0bf11de9a2536205cd0d0a7ede759714`\nBytes: 4129\nRelevance: Shows the ICAO/IATA mapping for the market-listed airports and the airports excepted in PX-2. This is relevant because PX-2's exception list includes only OISS/SYZ among the five market-listed airports, while plaintiff's secondary report says several listed airports remained operational.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Source-chain and adverse-check ledger\nPlaintiff searched official/NOTAM and reporting paths for the May 22-25 Iran airspace action. The strongest preserved source found is Notamify's raw OIIX A1010/26 NOTAM capture; plaintiff did not locate a direct Iranian CAA server copy during this phase. Indian Express corroborates Iran CAA issuance, timing, western Tehran FIR scope, CAA permission requirement, and commercial rerouting, but is secondary and partly source-attributed. Adverse issues checked: whether the action was merely foreign advisory/operator avoidance, weather, limited airport disruption, or outside the deadline. The admitted NOTAM text defeats those objections on preponderance, subject to the custody caveat that the raw NOTAM is from an archive capture rather than direct CAA retrieval.\n\n[defendant] Defense source-chain and scope analysis\nThe decisive scope issue is textual. Plaintiff's raw NOTAM is timely and likely non-weather, but its coded subject is QFALC, decoded as aerodrome closed, and its operative wording closes airports in the west part of Tehran FIR with specified airport exceptions and CAA permission requirements. The admitted airport-code mapping shows only OISS/SYZ overlaps between the NOTAM exception list and the five market-listed airports. The secondary report conflicts with the raw NOTAM's airport identifiers and is therefore weaker on exact scope. No direct Iranian CAA server copy has been admitted by either side.\n\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal check\nPlaintiff read defendant's Q-code and airport-code exhibits. The Q-code exhibit supports that QFALC is an aerodrome-closure code, but also states the code does not by itself decide the full operational scope and the plain text must be read. The airport-code exhibit shows the NOTAM exceptions include only Shiraz/SYZ among the five market-listed airports; that does not defeat the major-region theory and may support closure of other listed airports if within the west-Tehran-FIR closure.\n\n[defendant] Surrebuttal scope audit\nNo new source evidence was needed. Plaintiff's rebuttal concedes scope is decisive and relies on the major-region path. The admitted rule text requires commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from the relevant airspace or region. The admitted NOTAM and Q-code evidence remain airport/aerodrome-focused and do not show commercial transit through western Tehran FIR was broadly suspended or closed. The airport-code exhibit remains relevant both to the two-listed-airport pathway and to the weight of the secondary article's paraphrase.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-19T23:12:56.833707974Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C7","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C7","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":886759,"role_id":"council","turn_number":15},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":19,"version":36}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1781909890083},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Okay, let's tackle this step by step. The user is acting as Council Member C7 in an AAR case, and I need to submit a vote based on the provided evidence.\n\nFirst, I need to understand the proposition: Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The rule defines a major closure as either a broad suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major region, or a complete suspension affecting at least two listed airports.\n\nLooking at the evidence. The plaintiff submitted PX-2, a NOTAM capture from Notamify showing OIIX A1010/26. The NOTAM says \"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD EXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE OPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET...\" and requires new permission for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports.\n\nThen there's PX-3, an Indian Express report, which says Iran closed the western half of airspace, citing the NOTAM, and lists the eight airports remaining operational.\n\nDefendant's evidence includes DX-D, FAA Q-code decode: QFALC indicates aerodrome closed, not airspace closure. DX-E shows airport code mapping: the NOTAM's exception list includes OISS/SYZ (Shiraz) but none of the other four listed airports (IKA, THR, MHD, IFN) are in the exception list. So for the two-listed-airports path, only Shiraz is an exception, which doesn't meet two airports.\n\nBut the rule's first path is \"broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region.\" The NOTAM is about airports in the west Tehran FIR. The FIR covers a large airspace region. However, the Q-code QFALC is aerodrome-related. The FAA doc says the Q-code decode doesn't specify airspace overflight; the plain text must be read.\n\nThe NOTAM text says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed ones. But airports being closed could affect arrivals/departures at those airports, but what about transit? The rule requires \"transiting, arriving in, and departing from\" the airspace or region. If only airports are closed but overflights are allowed, does that count?\n\nThe NOTAM says \"all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed except...\", but doesn't mention airways or overflights. The Q-code is for aerodrome, not airway. So perhaps the closure is limited to airports, not the entire airspace. For transit (overflying), the NOTAM doesn't say anything. So commercial flights transiting through the FIR would not be affected, only those landing or taking off at the airports. \n\nBut the rule says \"transiting, arriving in, and departing from\". If the airports are closed, then arriving and departing is suspended. But transiting requires the airspace to be blocked. However, typically, if all airports in a region are closed, transiting flights might reroute, but the NOTAM may not explicitly prohibit overflights.\n\nThe defendant argues that the QFALC is aerodrome closure, not airspace closure. The FAA note says the code doesn't include airspace overflight details. The NOTAM text says \"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\" – but FIR (Flight Information Region) is a designated airspace. Closing all airports in the FIR doesn't necessarily mean the airspace is closed. Airports are on the ground; the airspace above might still be used for transiting. \n\nBut how does that work? If airports are closed, meaning flights can't land or take off, but overflights might be okay. However, if there's a closure of airspace, that affects all aircraft in that airspace. But the NOTAM is about airports being closed. \n\nThe rule's definition says \"a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region\". If all airports in the west Tehran FIR are closed, then arriving and departing from those airports is suspended. But what about transiting through the FIR? The NOTAM doesn't say anything about transiting. However, if all airports in the region are closed, but overflights are allowed, maybe the \"transiting\" aspect isn't covered. But if the airports are closed, the main impact is on arrivals and departures. However, the rule includes \"transiting, arriving in, and departing from\" – so perhaps suspending arrivals and departures at multiple airports in a region could count as part of the requirement, but transiting needs to be suspended as well. \n\nThe defendant's argument is that the QFALC code is for aerodrome closure, so it's airport-specific, not airspace. The FAA doc confirms that the Q-code for aerodrome doesn't dictate airspace routes. The NOTAM's text is about airports, so it might not cover transiting flights in the airspace. \n\nLooking at the market rule examples: Qualifying examples are like January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace (except for international flights with permission), which would cover both arrivals and overflights. The non-qualifying example is a partial closure around the Strait of Hormuz. \n\nAnother point: the market rule says \"a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region\". If the closure only affects arriving and departing at airports, but not transiting, does that count? But a \"major Iranian airspace region\" would likely include both. However, the notam is only about airports. \n\nWait, but if you close all airports in the west Tehran FIR, that means no flights can arrive or depart there. However, for transiting (passing through the FIR without landing), the NOTAM may or may not affect that. Typically, airport closure (closing airports) doesn't necessarily close the airspace. For example, military bases might close their airports but air traffic could still pass through. But in this case, the NOTAM says \"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\", which would mean airports are closed, but the FIR as a whole might not be closed. The FIR is a defined airspace; closing airports in it doesn't automatically close the FIR airspace for overflights. Unless the NOTAM explicitly says the airspace is closed, but in this case, it's referring to airports.\n\nSo the NOTAM is a closure of specific airports, but not the full airspace. The FAA Q-code decode supports that. So the closure is limited to airports, not the entire airspace region. Therefore, it doesn't qualify as a \"major closure\" of the airspace region because transit isn't affected. \n\nFor the second pathway: complete suspension at two listed airports. The listed airports are IKA (OIIE), THR (OIII), MHD (OIMM), SYZ (OISS), IFN (OIFM). The NOTAM exception list is OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW. So OISS (Shiraz/SYZ) is in the exception list. None of the others (OIIE/IKA, OIII/THR, OIMM/MHD, OIFM/IFN) are in the exception list. That implies those airports were closed. Wait, the NOTAM says \"all airports... closed except [...]\", so the listed airports except the ones in the exception are closed. So the airports not in the exception list are closed. The five market-listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, IFN. From the airport code mapping, SYZ is OISS, which is in the exception list (so it's open with restrictions), but the others (IKA=OIIE, THR=OIII, MHD=OIMM, IFN=OIFM) are not in the exception list. Therefore, those four airports are closed. However, the NOTAM states that all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except the listed ones. So the west Tehran FIR airports that are not on the exception list are closed. So the four airports (IKA, THR, MHD, IFN) are closed. But according to the exception list, only SYZ is open. But the NOTAM says the exception airports are operational from sunrise to sunset. So those airports are still open but with restrictions. \n\nFor the two-listed-airports pathway: the rule says \"complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports\". But the airports that were in the exception list (like SYZ) are still operating, so arrivals and departures aren't completely suspended there. The other listed airports (IKA, THR, MHD, IFN) are closed (since they're not in exception list). So for those four airports, arrivals and departures are suspended. However, are they \"complete suspension\"? The NOTAM says the closed airports are closed entirely? The NOTAM says \"all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed except the listed ones\", so yes, the non-exception airports are completely closed (no arrivals/departures). So for the four listed airports (IKA, THR, MHD, IFN), they are closed. So at least two of the listed airports have complete suspension. So maybe it qualifies. \n\nBut wait, the defense's DX-E shows that the market-listed airports (IKA=OIIE, THR=OIII, MHD=OIMM, SYZ=OISS, IFN=OIFM). The NOTAM's exception list includes OISS (SYZ), but not the others. So OIIE, OIII, OIMM, OIFM are not in the exception list, meaning they are closed. So those four airports are closed. So for those four, complet suspension of arrivals and departures. So meeting the two-airport pathway.\n\nBut the defendant argues that the secondary report (PX-3) says \"all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25\" and \"only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran’s Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas.\" Wait, the defense points out that PX-3's list includes Mehrabad (THR) and Imam Khomeini (IKA), which are in the market-listed airports. But according to the airport code mapping, both THR (OIII) and IKA (OIIE) are in the list of cities but are they in the exception? Let's check DX-E:\n\nThe captured CSV lines for the eight airports in the NOTAM's exception:\n\nOITR (Urmia), OIKK (Kerman), OIAA (Abadan), OISS (Shiraz), OIYY (Yazd), OICC (Kermanshah), OIGG (Rasht), OIAW (Ahvaz). So MHD (Mashhad) is OIMM, but OIMM isn't in the exception list. So MHD is closed. Similarly, IKA (OIIE) and THR (OIII) are not in the exception list. So according to the NOTAM, IKA, THR, MHD, IFN are closed. But PX-3 says \"including Tehran’s Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International\", which would imply those two airports are operational. That's a conflict. \n\nPX-3 says \"Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran’s Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas.\" But according to the CSV data, the exception list for NOTAM does not include OIII (THR) or OIIE (IKA), but does include OIAM (wait, no, the exception list has OIAA, OIKK, etc., but not OIII or OIIE). So according to the NOTAM, IKA and THR would be closed. But PX-3 says they're operational. So the secondary report (PX-3) is reporting that those airports are operational, but the NOTAM (as per the exception list) does not list them. So the secondary report has conflicting information with the NOTAM's exception list. \n\nThe defense is emphasizing that the raw NOTAM's exception list doesn't include IKA and THR, but the secondary report says they are operational, so this is a conflict. The raw NOTAM should have more weight, but the fact that PX-3 lists IKA and THR as operational suggests that the NOTAM exceptions might include them. But the CSV shows OIIE (IKA) and OIII (THR) are not in the exception list of the NOTAM. So according to the NOTAM, those airports should be closed. But PX-3 says they're operational. This conflict between the secondary report and the NOTAM's text. The defense says that the raw NOTAM takes precedence. \n\nSo the NOTAM's exception list includes only OISS/SYZ among the five market-listed airports. The other listed airports (IKA, THR, MHD, IFN) are not in the exception list, so they're closed. But PX-3 says Mehrabad (THR) and Imam Khomeini (IKA) are operational, which is a contradiction. So the secondary report's accuracy on those airports is questionable. \n\nBut the defense would argue that the raw NOTAM is the primary source, so the exception list is definitive. The secondary report may have made a mistake. Therefore, only SYZ (OISS) is open among the five market-listed airports. Wait, but the secondary report lists eight operational airports including IKA and THR, but the NOTAM's exception list doesn't include them. So there's a discrepancy. The defense would point out that the raw NOTAM doesn't list IKA and THR in the exceptions, so they are closed. But if the airports are closed, then arrivals and departures are completely suspended at those airports. But then the two-listed-airports pathway would require two of the listed airports to have complete suspension. So IKA, THR, MHD, IFN are closed (not exceptions), so those four are suspended. So two of them would suffice. But the problem is the conflict in the secondary report. However, the raw NOTAM is the primary source. So according to the raw NOTAM, IKA and THR are closed (not in exception list), so complete suspension. \n\nBut the rule says \"complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports\". If IKA and THR are closed (no arrivals or departures), then yes, two airports. Even though PX-3 says they're operational, the raw NOTAM has more weight. \n\nBut wait, the Q-code is QFALC, which FAA says is for aerodrome closed. The rule's two-listed-airports path says \"complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports\". So each airport's arrangements. If IKA and THR are closed, as per NOTAM, then yes, complete suspension at two airports. \n\nBut wait, the NOTAM says \"all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed except [...]\". The exception list does not include IKA and THR, so those airports are closed – meaning no arrivals or departures. So yes, complete suspension for those airports. Therefore, the two-listed-airports pathway is met. \n\nOn the other hand, the defense's argument is that the NOTAM is airport-specific, not airspace. But the rule's definition for the airport pathway explicitly says \"complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports\". So that's satisfied here. \n\nSo if two listed airports have complete suspension, then it qualifies. The market list includes IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, IFN. From NOTAM's exception list (for airports that are open), only SYZ is listed. The others are not in exception list, so they are closed. Therefore, IKA, THR, MHD, IFN are closed (complete suspension). So at least two of these five airports are affected, which qualifies under the second pathway. \n\nBut wait, the exception list includes OISS (SYZ), but the others (OIIE, OIII, OIMM, OIFM) are not present, so they're closed. So yes, four of the five listed airports are closed. So it meets the requirement. \n\nBut the defense's DX-S4 data shows the airport codes. Let's check the captured CSV:\n\nMarked-listed airports:\n\nOIIE is IKA (Imam Khomeini)\n\nOIII is THR (Mehrabad)\n\nOIMM is MHD (Mashhad)\n\nOISS is SYZ (Shiraz)\n\nOIFM is IFN (Isfahan)\n\nNow, looking at the NOTAM exception list airports:\n\nOITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW.\n\nSo OISS is there (Shiraz). But the other four listed airports (OIIE, OIII, OIMM, OIFM) are not in the exception list. Therefore, they are closed. So the complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures for these four airports (each of which is a listed airport), thus meeting the requirement of two or more. \n\nSo the second pathway qualifies. Therefore, the proposition is demonstrated. \n\nBut wait, the defense mentions that in PX-3, the Indian Express report lists Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini as operational. But according to the NOTAM's exception list, they're not there. So there's a discrepancy. However, the raw NOTAM is the primary source; secondary reports may have errors. The NOTAM is specific on which airports are exceptions. So if those airports aren't in the exception list, they're closed. So even if the news report says they're open, the actual NOTAM says they're closed. But maybe the news report is wrong. The primary source should take precedence. \n\nTherefore, the second pathway is satisfied (two airports closed), and it's a major closure as per the rule. \n\nBut also, the first pathway: a broad closure of a major Iranian airspace region. The west Tehran FIR is a major region. If all airports there are closed (except eight), but what about transiting? The NOTAM may not cover transiting, but the second pathway is sufficient. \n\nThe rule says either pathway qualifies. Since the second pathway (two-listed-airports) is met, the vote should be \"demonstrated\".\n\nThe rationale should be concise: three sentences max. So state that the NOTAM closed four listed airports (IKA, THR, MHD, IFN), satisfying the two-airport requirement under the rule. The raw NOTAM is the authoritative source, and the defense's secondary report conflict has lower weight. Thus, proposition is demonstrated.\n\nWait, but in the NOTAM, it says \"all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed except [...]\", and the exceptions are a list of eight airports. The five market-listed airports include SYZ in exceptions, but the other four not. So four airports closed. Hence, two or more closed. So yes.\n\nSo vote: demonstrated.\n\nRationale: The NOTAM closed four market-listed airports (Imam Khomeini, Mehrabad, Mashhad, Isfahan), meeting the rule's requirement for two airports with complete suspension. The raw NOTAM is authoritative, and secondary reports do not override its specific airport closures.\n\nYes. That seems correct.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_0fd519e105614f8ab01ced","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The NOTAM closed four listed airports (IKA, THR, MHD, IFN) with complete suspension of arrivals/departures, satisfying the rule's two-airport pathway. Raw NOTAM text is authoritative over secondary reports. Limited exceptions do not negate the closure under the rule.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":26818,"output":4303,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":31121,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cac